Background


The Paleobiology Database (PBDB) is a public database of paleontological data that anyone can use, maintained by an international non-governmental group of paleontologists.

It contains published data on the taxonomy, and temporal and geographic distributions of fossil occurrences. It also contains bibliographic data to which all of the other data types are linked.

Who
The Paleobiology Database (PBDB) organized by a non-governmental, non-profit group of volunteer professional and graduate student paleontologists. Those without graduate-level training may still be able to contribute under the guidance of an authorized member.

When
The PBDB originated from the NCEAS-funded Phanerozoic Marine Paleofaunal Database initiative (1998 2000).
During the periods of 2000 2008 and 2010 2013, it received funding from the US National Science Foundation has also received funding from the Australian Research Council.

Limitations

  1. Sources: Reports may be spatially biased as contributions are voluntary
  2. Data Entry errors are possible

License
The PBDB is publically available and may be used freely with attribution (i.e., citation) under a CC BY 4.0 International License.

How to Cite
You can cite the specific Data Archive or the specific download including with it the date and parameters of the download. The example given they give is below.

Citation
The data were downloaded from the Paleobiology Database on 13 December, 2013, using the group name marine and the following parameters: time intervals = Eocene and Oligocene, region = Europe, paleoenvironment = marine, Order = Cetacea.

Parameters

Object of Observation: Plants or animals from the Mississippian period located in present-day Pennsylvania
Object of Analysis Mississippian period fossils found, reported, and entered into the PBDB within Pennsylvania
Data-set Population Fossils of any time period recorded in the PBDB and found within PA as of the date of PA_fossils.xlsx download
Mark/Variable Yes, see section Data Description for full list

Make Spatial

#-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#                                SPATIAL
#                   packages: USAboundaries, elevatr
#-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
st.pa_border <- st_transform(us_states(states = "pennsylvania"), 6346)

elevation.utm <- get_elev_raster(st.pa_border, z = 5, clip = "locations")

#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#                         CONVERT FOSSIL DATA
#---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
sf.fossils <- st_as_sf(df.fossils, coords = c("Long", "Lat"), crs = 4326) %>%
  st_transform(sf.fossils, crs = 26918)

# Check All In Same Projection
proj.pa_border <- raster::projection(st.pa_border)
proj.elevation <- raster::projection(elevation.utm)
proj.fossils <- raster::projection(sf.fossils)

Projections
PA State Border: +proj=utm +zone=17 +ellps=GRS80 +towgs84=0,0,0,0,0,0,0 +units=m +no_defs
Fossils Data: +proj=utm +zone=18 +datum=NAD83 +units=m +no_defs
Elevation Raster: +proj=utm +zone=17 +ellps=GRS80 +units=m +no_defs

# Fix Projections
st.pa_border <- st_transform(st.pa_border, crs(sf.fossils))
elevation.utm <- projectRaster(elevation.utm, crs = crs(sf.fossils))
# check
proj.pa_border <- raster::projection(st.pa_border)
proj.elevation <- raster::projection(elevation.utm)

Point Pattern Analysis

# Converts stateowin to a "window" file format
state.window <- as.owin(st.pa_border)

# Turn sf data into a ppp format, then set the window
ppp.fossils <- as.ppp(sf.fossils)
Window(ppp.fossils) <- state.window

# plot
par(mar = c(2.5, 3, 1, 1))
plot(elevation.utm)
plot(ppp.fossils,
  use.marks = F,
  cex = 1,
  pch = 4,
  lwd = 1.3,
  add = TRUE,
  main.title = "Fossils against Elevation in PA",
  xaxt = "n",
  yaxt = "n"
)

The data appears to be spatially dependent. There are several clusters, most notably in the Southeastern region. Clustering is considered positive autocorrelation. There are regions of dispersal as well, notably in the central to North-central region, which would be negative autocorrelation.

It is likely that there are several factors at play here.

  1. First Order Autocorrelation: This is a cause of clustering by correlation with itself, i.e., the presence of one observation increases the chances of another observation nearby. This makes sense for fossils because the plants and animals they come from were also first-order autocorrelated.
  2. Second Order Autocorrelation: This is a cause of clustering by correlation with some other (known or unknown) factor. For example, the fossils are constrained to certain areas because the fossilization process has specific environmnetal requirements to work.
  3. Randomness: In empirical research, stochastic processes are always present to some degree. Its possible the observed pattern is entirely due to randomness.

Centrography

#-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#                                CENTROGRAPHY
#                       packages: RColorBrewer, car
#-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
mycolors <- brewer.pal(n = 11, name = "BrBG")[-c(1, 2, 10, 11)]
plot(elevation.utm, 
     col = mycolors
     )

dataEllipse(ppp.fossils$x, ppp.fossils$y,
  levels = 0.68,
  fill = TRUE, 
  fill.alpha = 0.1, # Fill the ellipse with transparent grey
  pch = 4, 
  cex = 1, # little x's
  xlab = "x (m)", 
  ylab = "y (m)",
  col = c(rgb(red = 0, green = 0, blue = 0, alpha = 0.5), "blue"), 
  add = TRUE
)

Standard Ellipse: An elliptical region around the spatial average (center) of the data and encapsulates any given amount of spatial spread.

  • Because it is standardized, it can more easily be used for comparison with other data sets.
  • Approximately 68% of points fall within the ellipse given by levels = 0.68

Point Pattern Autocorrelation

Density-Based

Global

#-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#                                GLOBAL
#                       packages: spatstat
#-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
area <- area.owin(state.window) / (1000 * 1000) # convert m^2 to km^2

The global density is approximately 442 fossils reported per km2

Local: Kernel

#-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#                                LOCAL
#-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# R will work in metres by default, let's switch to km
ppp.fossils_km <- rescale(ppp.fossils, 1000, "km")

# Using varying bandwiths bandwidth (sigma)
ker.density_1km <- density(ppp.fossils_km, sigma = 1)
ker.density_10km <- density(ppp.fossils_km, sigma = 10)
ker.density_100km <- density(ppp.fossils_km, sigma = 100)

plot(ker.density_1km, main = "sigma = 1km", las = 1)
contour(ker.density_1km, add = TRUE)

plot(ker.density_10km, main = "sigma = 10km", las = 1)
contour(ker.density_10km, add = TRUE)

plot(ker.density_100km, main = "sigma = 100km", las = 1)
contour(ker.density_100km, add = TRUE)

Bandwidth: Changes the size of effect field for each point. Higher bandwidth therefore results in a smoother output appearance while the lower bandwidths have fewer, smaller, more distinct cluster areas.

  • Small Sigma: Appears similar to what is expected from an independent random process (IRP), but still possible for some first or second order effects.
  • Large Sigma: Appears distinctly brightest in the Southeast area and steadily decreases towards the Northwest. This type of regular pattern is what is expected from spatial autocorrelation.
#-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#                       packages: maptools, spatstat
#-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# convert elevation to a special format
elev.img <- as.im.RasterLayer(elevation.utm)

# calculate the relationship
densityfossil.vs.elevation <- rhohat(unmark(ppp.fossils), elev.img)

plot(densityfossil.vs.elevation)

The graph suggests that there is a greater relative density of observations at higher elevations, whereas at lower elevations the density is relatively lower. At 400m elevation, the density switches from higher than average to lower than average as indicated by the dotted red line.

The grey region is an estimate of uncertainty. With proper experiment design, we would expect the true population value to be within that region most of the time, although it could potentially be anywhere.

Distance-Based

Global: Nearest Neighbor

# For each point, nndist calculates the distance to the nearest point
nn.fossils <- nndist(ppp.fossils_km)

# plot
hist(nn.fossils,
  main = NULL, las = 1,
  xlab = list("Distance between each point and its Nearest Neighbour (km)", cex = .8)
)

# look at the summary
skim(nn.fossils)

H0: The points are randomly distributed
HA: The points are significantly more dispersed or significantly more clustered than expected (two-tailed test)

clarkevans.test(ppp.fossils_km)
## 
##  Clark-Evans test
##  No edge correction
##  Z-test
## 
## data:  ppp.fossils_km
## R = 0.66511, p-value < 0.00000000000000022
## alternative hypothesis: two-sided

p < 0.01 meaning it is unlikely a pattern with this level of clustering was caused only by an IRP, although it is possible.

Local: L Functions

#-----------------------------------------------------------------
# Calculate the L function and its uncertainty envelope
#-----------------------------------------------------------------
lfun.data <- Lest(ppp.fossils_km)

lenv.data <- envelope(ppp.fossils_km, Lest,
  correction = "Ripley",
  verbose = F,
  nsim = 200, nrank = 1,
  savepatterns = TRUE, savefuns = TRUE
)

#-----------------------------------------------------------------
# Plot the raw L-function data for different edge effects
#-----------------------------------------------------------------
plot(lfun.data, . - r ~ r,
  ylim = c(
    0 - (max(lfun.data$iso - lfun.data$r)),
    max(lfun.data - lfun.data$r)
  )
)
# Add the uncertainty envelope.
plot(lenv.data, . - r ~ r,
  add = TRUE
)
